<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-646-574  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 646 574.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Business Week  July 23 1990 n3170 p30(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>'Killer' computer viruses: an idea whose time shouldn't come.andO;(Commentary) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lewyn, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Department of Defense (DOD) is receiving responses to itsRFP for the development and use of computer viruses as militaryweapons.andP;  The DOD's idea is to use viruses to attack, inhibitand/or destroy an enemy's communications equipment.andP;  Softwarepublishers and computer hackers express interest in developingviruses that would be simple and relatively inexpensive means ofdamaging an enemy's computer systems, data networks andtelecommunications.andP;  Analysts and critics of the DOD's RFP believesuch a scheme could backfire since it is the US's computer andcommunications systems that are the most technologically advancedand hence most vulnerable to attacks by computer viruses.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer virusesUnited States. Department of DefenseRequest for ProposalsWeaponsMilitaryCommunications Equipment.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>